Please add the possibility to filter out the tags in the TAGS list:
* by date (e.g. show tags no older than a 6 months);
* by name (e.g. show tags whose name matches a given pattern);
* by tagger.

Thank you,
Claudio Rosati

I'm trying to use the [git-hooks|https://www.npmjs.com/package/git-hooks] NPM package to install some hooks in my Git repository. However Sourcetree doesn't play nice with this as the hooks it installs uses the node shebang (#!/usr/bin/env node). However node isn't in the PATH specified in Sourcetree, the path is as follows

{noformat}
/Applications/SourceTree.app/Contents/Resources/git_local/libexec/git-core:/Applications/SourceTree.app/Contents/Resources/bin:/Applications/SourceTree.app/Contents/Resources/git_local/bin:/Applications/SourceTree.app/Contents/Resources/git_local/gitflow:/Applications/SourceTree.app/Contents/Resources/git_local/git-lfs:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin
{noformat}

node is installed in /usr/local/bin/node which is normally on the path.

Sourcetree should include the user's $PATH variable into its own path when executing hooks.

When I do a "Reset to Commit" on a file that was previous deleted in a past commit and that path no longer exists, the command fails with
{code}
error: pathspec 'error: pathspec 'scripts/queries/some_file_name.sql' did not match any file(s) known to git.'
{code}

When I look at the command that was issued, it is calling reset (which is technically correct), but that will not work because the path really does not exist (except back in the previous commit). I added a custom command to fix this so I can do it without having to use the command line. That command is this
{code}
git checkout $SHA^ -- $FILE
{code}

While using a custom command works just fine, it would be nice if that Reset to Commit was smart enough to detect if that path still exists and then based on that info, either use the "git reset" command if it does exist, otherwise use the "git checkout sha^" command if that path does not exist.
